ELK (Elastic Stack)
Why Continuous Monitoring?
Continuous Monitoring is an important part of software development. It is something we take up as measure to maintain the health of a software and to improve the quality of the software, and this is based on the feed back we get from the insights grained from monitoring.

Types of Monitoring
•	System Performance – System performance refers to the speed, efficiency, and resource utilization of a computer system, measured by metrics like responsiveness, throughput, and latency. It is determined by hardware (CPU, RAM, storage) and software optimization. Key ways to improve it include monitoring resources, removing startup apps, clearing disk space, and updating drivers
•	Process monitoring – Specific process how it is getting handled, process are running or not, how is the health status of processes
•	Integration – Integration monitoring is the proactive process of tracking, analysing, and managing the health, performance, and data integrity of connections between software applications.
•	Application Performance – the practice of tracking software application metrics—such as response times, error rates, and resource utilization—to ensure optimal performance and user experience. It enables teams to proactively detect, diagnose, and resolve technical issues using transaction tracing, log analysis, and real-time alerts to reduce downtime
•	Business Monitoring – It is used to monitor business improvement like customer data, which customer is interested in which product based on that it will provide the adds to the customer. It is basically monitoring the customer activity. Also, it will track the record of your selling and buying history so this will help you how much profit and loss you have met.
