What is ELK Stack?
ELK stack is a set of open-source tools that allow us to monitor, collect, process analyse & visualize data, this data can be of different types and formats and from almost any source. It was developed by Elastic co. iteratively. They started with Elastic search and kept on adding more tools to the stack. The primary purpose of ELK stack is log management.

ELK Features
•	System & Application Performance
•	Logging
•	Stack Security & Alerting
•	Scalability & Resiliency
•	Dashboards & Visualisations

ELK Stack Tools
Logstash is an open-source, server-side data processing pipeline that ingests data from diverse sources simultaneously, transforms it on the fly, and sends it to a "stash" like Elasticsearch
Filebeat is a lightweight, open-source log shipper and centralizer for the Elastic Stack, designed to monitor, collect, and forward log files to Elasticsearch or Logstash. It runs as a persistent agent, efficiently handling large data volumes, and can be deployed in containers (Docker, Kubernetes) or on servers
Elasticsearch is a distributed, open-source search and analytics engine based on Apache Lucene, designed for speed and scalability. It stores data as schema-free JSON documents, enabling fast full-text search, structured queries, and analytics, often used for log monitoring, security analytics, and AI
Kibana is a powerful, open-source data visualization and exploration tool designed for Elasticsearch. It serves as the visualization layer of the Elastic Stack (ELK Stack), allowing users to analyse, visualize, and build interactive dashboards on top of data stored in Elasticsearch indices, including logs, metrics, and security data.
X-Pack is an Elastic Stack extension that bundles security, alerting, monitoring, reporting, and graph capabilities.
Server-->Data collection-->FileBeat-->Buffe -->Logstash(Filtering & Processing)-->Elasticsearch(Indexing & Storing)-->Kibana(Analysis & Visualisation)
